node.text:
Our August cover star @GigiHadid embarks on her dream cake-baking internship under #CakeBoss's own @BuddyValastro, the prolific baker of cakes best known for his impressive larger-than-life cake designs. Here, Gigi talks cooking and baking with her family on the farm, everything bagel pregnancy cravings, and favorite ‘Cake Boss’ moments.

Director: @isabel.c.montes
Producer: @kriceee
Editor + Colorist: @ericaharperdillman
Director of Photography: @mr_dume
Camera: @22jezu
Audio: @dave_scaringe_sound
Stylist: @mimicuttrell
Makeup Artist: @cgonzalezbeauty
Hair Stylist: @jennifer_yepez
Special thanks to @carlosbakery

node.title: Gigi Hadid Shows Off Her Cake Decorating Skills With Cake Boss

“Slipping into the high heels that were just within arm’s reach on the rack behind me and watching how my legs, already long, began to extend to the heavens reminded me that nakedness was indeed much more a punishment than clothes, because who doesn’t want to rise to the heavens with the stomp of a foot?” writes acclaimed playwright @JeremyOHarris for our August issue. “This is why, for most of 2020, as sweatpants became de rigueur on Instagram for my peers, I began reaching deeper in my closet. I found myself draped on my couch in red-carpet finery as I streamed ‘The Queen’s Gambit’ and ‘Madoka Magica’ for hours. The idea of not reaching for the heavens while trapped in the hell of my apartment was unthinkable.” Tap the link in bio to read the full essay from our August issue, where Harris reflects on the thrills of getting dressed–whether or not anyone is there to see.

Initially, #ThomasinMcKenzie wanted nothing to do with acting. “I knew that it wasn’t as glamorous a job as you might expect from the outside,” says McKenzie, who grew up on far-flung movie sets around the world as the daughter of actor and drama coach Miranda Harcourt and writer and director Stuart McKenzie (her maternal grandmother is also New Zealand actress Kate Harcourt). “I wanted to be anything else.” It wasn’t until she was 13, when she played a younger version of sexual-abuse survivor and activist Louise Nicholas in the 2014 film ‘Consent,’ that she saw the power of storytelling to effect change and decided to pursue acting as a career. “It was a really tough role, and that opened my eyes to the fact that through acting, you get a chance to have a voice.” Read the full story from our August issue at the link in bio.

node.text: Prince Harry is set to open up like never before. Per an official press release, the Duke of Sussex has written a forthcoming memoir about his life. “I’m writing this not as the prince I was born but as the man I have become,” he wrote in a statement. “I’ve worn many hats over the years, both literally and figuratively, and my hope is that in telling my story—the highs and lows, the mistakes, the lessons learned—I can help show that no matter where we come from, we have more in common than we think.” The book is due for a Fall 2022 release and will be published by Penguin Random House. Tap the link in bio for everything we know about his memoir so far.

node.text:
Griff (@wiffygriffy) is doing things her own way. Though the breakout pop artist took home this year’s BRITs Rising Star Award (past winners include Adele, Sam Smith, and Jorja Smith), she’s focusing on staying grounded. “I think with these awards, obviously they’re incredible, but they don’t change what we do,” she says. “It’s not the reason why I do it.” The 20-year-old singer  recently dropped her seven-track mixtape ‘One Foot in Front of the Other,’ with songs about healing after heartbreak that range from unique, sticky indie-pop melodies to melancholy ballads. “I just want people to feel emotion when they listen to it, whether it's happy or sad or warm or nostalgic. I want people to feel and relate to my songs in their own ways.” At the link in bio, she talks learning how to walk a tightrope, her one-of-a-kind fashion, and sharing fries with Taylor Swift.

node.text: There are plenty of boot trends to choose now, but there’s only one that is truly meant for walking: the kitten-heel boot. node.text: “Fashion is not ‘art,’” @maisonvalentino creative director Pierpaolo Piccioli (@pppiccioli) wrote in the notes accompanying his Valentino Des Ateliers show. But one might beg to differ after witnessing his bravura performance today at the Arsenale, home of the Venice Biennale. Together with curator @Gianluigi_Ricuperati, Piccioli assembled a dream team of 16 international contemporary artists as collaborators. The results were sculptural and featured grandiose ball gowns, balloon jackets, and bubble hem minidresses underneath giant trembling ostrich frond hats by master milliner @PhilipTreacy, all awash in vibrant color. See more at the link in bio.

node.text: It’s official: Surrealism is staging a fashion comeback. “Considering we’re still amidst a global pandemic on the heels of plenty of political unrest, surrealism’s next generation in fashion makes a lot of sense,” writes @KristenvBateman. “After all, the motive of the original surrealists was to make the familiar strange, and to show a fragile world full of tension in a new, dream-like state.” At the link in bio, Bateman tracks the movement’s resurgence on the runway, from @Schiaparelli, @ChanelOfficial and beyond.

“During my pregnancy, I had one journal that I called my good journal and one journal that I called my bad journal,” says @GigiHadid for our August cover story. “They weren’t that literal, but one was more for the memories, for Khai. Maybe one day I’ll give her the bad journal just to be real about it.” What was inside the “bad” journal? “Anxieties and days where I felt like, ’Am I good enough to be a mom?’” she explains. “I didn’t want to feel guilty about feeling those things or writing those things down. I just liked the separation.” At the link in bio, the supermodel talks to @durgapolashi about becoming a mother, co-parenting with @Zayn, and coming into her own.
